snippet.textDisplay:
Former early '08 Mac Pro owner here. Said it before, and saying it again. I'm done with Apple. Either it's too expensive and overpowered or it's too expensive and under-powered. My beloved Mac Pro served me well for 12yrs. Not bad for $2500. But I simply can't justify the cost of their new lineup.
So I went back to Winblows 10...which honestly isn't half as bad as I was expecting once I figured out how to get it under control (O&O ShutUP and a few add-ons to make it look a lot like Mac's interface). Other than file explorer (which I honestly like better than mac's folder system) and the taskbar, it's pretty much all the same.

snippet.textDisplay: Even considering the  concerns over noise you should have gone for air-cooling .  The real Mac Pro uses a passive heatsink but the chassis fans and airflow are so effective that everything remains well within its thermal limits even when under extreme workloads.  Ultimately, there's no real reason why your Hackinosh couldn't have achieved very similar temperatures given that virtually all components besides are motherboard are identical those the Mac Pro.  In your video "challenging the Mac Pro", which was uploaded about a month before this series began, you used a Noctua NH-U14S DX-3647  - I assume this was discarded in favor of liquid cooling  in light of your acoustic targets, but selecting and appointing fans for optimal air-cooling should have been a part of your challenge since this was one of Apple's key design elements.  Nonetheless, a highly entertaining finale.  incidentally, do you mention which CPU you use in the parts list?
